Comprehension:
We translated the Mishnah:
< האיש מקדש בו ובשלוחו
< האשה מתקדשת בה ובשלוחה
< האיש מקדש את בתו כשהיא נערה בו ובשלוחו:
> A man can be _mekadesh_ a woman himself or with a _shaliach_
> A woman can accept _kiddushin_ herself or with her _shaliach_
> A man can be makdesh his daughter when she is 12.5 years old, himself or via his shaliach
Now that we have a basic understanding of the Mishnah, let’s ask some comprehension questions.
Let’s ask a question about the Mishnah in general.
If I say “you’re invited to come drive to my wedding,” what might I mean by that? What are the ways that you can understand my extra specificity?
Maybe I mean you’re invited _only_ if you come by car, i.e, I might be speaking _“davka”_ i.e. intentionally specifically. 
Or, I might mean you’re invited _for example_ by car, i.e. I might mean it _“lav davka,”_ i.e. “not specifically,” just as an illustration of how you might do it, but coming by other methods is fine as well.
Lastly, I might mean you can come _even_ by car, i.e, I may be telling you the most surprising option, but maybe it’s obvious that you can also come via any method that is less surprising, i.e, my specificity is in order to teach you the “biggest chiddish i.e. surprise,” and I’m expecting you to infer all less surprising options from it.
So, we can ask, when the Mishnah makes a list of options, does it mean those options as _davka_, i.e. those are the only options, _lav davka_, they are illustrations, but there may be other options, or are they the _biggest chiddish i.e surprise_, that the Mishnah is telling us the most surprising option, and we are supposed to infer from it all less surprising options also work?
Let’s remember the question as we move forward. 
